1ï¸âƒ£ Count frequency of characters in a String
ğŸ’¡ Logic

Use HashMap

Character = key, frequency = value

Traverse string once


ğŸ§  Core Logic (Before Code â€“ Interviewers LOVE this)

â€œWe traverse the string character by character.
For each character, we store and update its count in a HashMap.
If the character is already present, we increase its count, otherwise we initialize it with 1.â€

ğŸ“Œ Why HashMap?

Fast lookup â†’ O(1)

Stores key = character, value = frequency




import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s = "java";
        
        // Step 1: Create map to store character frequency
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        // Step 2: Traverse each character
        for (char ch : s.toCharArray()) {

            // Step 3: Increase count if exists, else put 1
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        // Step 4: Print result
        System.out.println(map);
    }
}


â± Time & Space Complexity (Must Say)

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

Where n = length of string

ğŸ¤ How to Explain in Interview (Perfect Answer)

â€œI iterate through the string and store character frequencies in a HashMap.
I use getOrDefault to simplify frequency updates.
This gives O(n) time complexity with a single traversal.â€

ğŸ”¥ Interview Follow-Up Questions
â“ Can you do it without HashMap?

â¡ Yes, using array of size 26 (only lowercase letters)

â“ What if string has uppercase also?

â¡ Use array of size 52 or normalize using Character.toLowerCase()

â“ What about ASCII characters?

â¡ Use array of size 256

â“ Why not nested loops?

â¡ That would be O(nÂ²) â€“ inefficient
